entry.title: Substitute missing color parameters before premultiplying
entry.content:
https://drafts.csswg.org/css-color-4/#interpolation-missing

"""

If a color with a carried forward missing component is interpolated

with another color which is not missing that component, the missing

component is treated as having the other color’s component value.

"""



We doing this after pre-multiplication, which lead to spurious

results, for example:



color-mix(in lab, lab(none 0 0), lab(100 0 0 / 0.6)



Should give the color:



lab(100 0 0 / 0.8)



But because we were pre-multiplying the second colors lightness with

0.5, and un-premultiplying with the interpolated alpha of 0.8, we were

instead getting:



lab(62.5 0 0 / 0.8)

entry.title: Remove Skia layer staging flags
entry.content:
With the removal of SK_RESOLVE_FILTERS_BEFORE_RESTORE, the output of

an image filter will be drawn directly to the parent surface.

Previously if there were any deferred effects like a color filter or

a transform, they would be resolved into another offscreen surface and

then that would be drawn 1-to-1 with the parent. Additionally,

drawImage now maps directly to drawImageRect. drawImage() had an

optimization when the canvas transform was pixel-aligned and the image

was 1-to-1 with the surface, and there was a clip matching the image

bounds, then SkCanvas would skip auto-adding a saveLayer for the image

filter and would evaluate the image filter on the input image

directly. Now drawImageRect has a similar optimization except that it

is for any image or subset image, so long as it's not an alpha-only

color type or the paint also has a SkMaskFilter to evaluate.



With the removal SK_USE_LEGACY_CONTENT_BOUNDS_PROPAGATION, the known

content bounds provided as a hint to saveLayer() are propagated

through the entire image filter graph. Previously in deep image graphs

the content bounds would be replaced with the desired output bounds,

and only intersected with the content bounds at the end if the filter

graph didn't affect transparent black. Propagating content bounds all

the way through the graph does not lose any information and can yield

smaller required input layer bounds.



Both of these changes can result in imperceptible pixel diffs because

image dimensions being sampled from change, or from skipping an

offscreen surface that encoded colors down to 8-bits.

entry.title: [infra] Fix the unused suites check.
entry.content:
The current code checks for unused tests after flattening test suites,

so self.test_suites maps from suite name to suite definition regardless

of whether the suite is a basic suite or one of the compound suite

types. When resolving sub suites, all of the suites are treated the

same, so when resolving sub suites for a basic suite, it's actually

adding the names of tests to resolved suites. This means that if a suite

has the same name as a test in some other suite that is used, the first

suite will show up as used regardless of whether it is or not.



This changes it so that we check if tests are used before flattening the

test suites. This makes it simple to resolve sub suites only for the

compound suite types. Doing so reveals that the variations_smoke_tests

basic suite is actually unused.

entry.content:
The MigrateFlocAllowedToAnnotationsTable is testing the existence of

column 'publicly_routable' after the migration; which is incorrect

since the column is removed in version 48.

ASSERT_TRUE(db.DoesColumnExist("visits", "publicly_routable"));



The unittests was passing since the DoesColumnExists doesn't reload

the schema and it is testing the condition on the original (not

entry.title: Cleanup GetTransform methods in OpenXrController
entry.content:
Based upon its (correct) assignment to XrInputSourceDescription's

input_from_pointer member, the `GetPointerFromGripTransform` method is

inaccurately named, since the current name implies that it returns

`pointer_from_grip` while actually it returns `grip_from_pointer`

(`input_from_pointer` is perhaps a bit unfortunately named, and `grip`

can be used interchangeably with how it uses `input`). This change

thus renames the method to `GetGripFromPointerTransform`, which is more

accurate.



Some of this confusion likely came from the ambiguously named

`GetTransformFromSpaces` method, which *does* indeed return the

`origin_from_target` transform. This method was *also* renamed to be

more clear, to `GetOriginFromTarget`. In doing so, the order of the

spaces passed in was also swapped so that the order matched the new

method name. This was only called by two methods locally, and verified

via WMR that they were both flipped appropriately. This method also

did not access any local state and was abstracte to an anonymous

namespace function, which would better facilitate moving it out of this

class if that becomes necessary in the future.

entry.title: [Responsive Toolbar] Fix animating layout bug.
entry.content:
Animating layout could get stuck in a state where its current layout

size was zero, which meant it was never rendered, which meant it never

had a chance to invalidate and recalculate its preferred size.



This resulted in a fully-collapsed animating layout embedded in a flex

layout when it was first rendered (e.g. a ToolbarIconContainer in a

narrow browser window) never being able to un-collapse and show its

contents, even if the browser window was made larger.



This CL bypasses the "does the current layout fit in the available

space?" check if the current layout is empty in the default

AnimatingLayoutManager flex rule.



This means if the current layout is empty, the flex rule returns the

correct size for e.g. _x_ and _x0 queries, which are important in the

initial FlexLayout setup.

entry.title: [ios] Change DeserializeWebStateList() to only accept empty list
entry.content:
DeserializeWebStateList is only called when loading session from the

disk at startup at which point the list is empty.



The requirement to load in a non-empty WebStateList was coming from

"load after crash" (long gone) and "undo close all" (obsolete as it

is now implemented with TabsCloser).



This simplify both the implementation and the tests as there are less

edge cases to consider now (i.e. are pinned tabs enabled, and is the

code using protobuf or Objective-C message).
